ting the container, such as</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>ubuntu@instance:~$ docker run -d -it -p 25565:25565 --name mc itzg/minecraft-server\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With that you can attach and interact at any time using</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>ubuntu@instance:~$ docker attach mc\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>and then Control-p Control-q to&nbsp;<strong>detach</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For remote access, configure your Docker daemon to use a&nbsp;<code>tcp</code>&nbsp;socket (such as&nbsp;<code>-H tcp://0.0.0.0:2375</code>) and attach from another machine:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>ubuntu@instance:~$ docker -H $HOST:2375 attach mc\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unless you\'re on a home/private LAN, you should&nbsp;<a href=\"https://docs.docker.com/articles/https/?ref=deviofuzz.com\">enable TLS access</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Making your own Minecraft server using Docker','','inherit','closed','closed','','141-revision-v1','','','2023-04-07 19:22:34','2023-04-07 19:22:34','',141,'http://deviofuzz.local/?p=142',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (143,1,'2023-04-07 19:23:04','2023-04-07 19:23:04','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Last updated on&nbsp;Feb 26, 2023</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1504639725590-34d0984388bd?crop=entropy&amp;cs=tinysrgb&amp;fit=max&amp;fm=jpg&amp;ixid=MnwxMTc3M3wwfDF8c2VhcmNofDF8fGhhY2tlcnxlbnwwfHx8fDE2NzczMzU0OTY&amp;ixlib=rb-4.0.3&amp;q=80&amp;w=960\" alt=\"Making your Linux home server more &quot;safe&quot;\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Photo by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://unsplash.com/@ikukevk?utm_source=ghost&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=api-credit\">Kevin Ku</a>&nbsp;/&nbsp;<a href=\"https://unsplash.com/?utm_source=ghost&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=api-credit\">Unsplash</a></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are a list of recommended steps to make your Linux server a little bit more protected against hackers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Always update your packages, and make them automatically update.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>#Manual Updates:  ubuntu@instance:~$ sudo apt update  ubuntu@instance:~$ sudo apt dist-upgrade    #Automatic Updates:  ubuntu@instance:~$ sudo apt install unattended-upgrades  ubuntu@instance:~$ sudo dpkg-reconfigure --priority=low unattended-upgrades </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Don\'t use root for everything, create your own user and give it privileges for sudo.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&gt;: sudo adduser &lt;username&gt;\n&gt;: sudo usermod -aG sudo &lt;username&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Use Private/Public keys instead of passwords. Passwords can be broken easily.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>#Create the Public Key Directory on your Linux Server \n&gt;: mkdir ~/.ssh &amp;&amp; chmod 700 ~/.ssh \n\n#Create Public/Private keys on your computer \n&gt;: ssh-keygen -b 4096 \n\n#Upload your Public key to the your Linux Server (Windows) \n&gt;: scp $env:USERPROFILE/.ssh/id_rsa.pub &lt;username&gt;@&lt;server ip&gt;:~/.ssh/authorized_keys \n\n#Send your Public key to the your Linux Server (MAC) \n&gt;: scp ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub &lt;username&gt;@&lt;server_ip&gt;:~/.ssh/authorized_keys \n\n#Send your Public key to the your Linux Server (LINUX) \n&gt;: ssh-copy-id &lt;username&gt;@&lt;server_ip&gt; </code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. Change your ssh config file to lock some kind of root access and password access</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4.1 Edit your ssh config file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&gt;: sudo vim /etc/ssh/sshd_config</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4.1.1 Change the default port used for ssh. The default one is 22, change for something different like 713.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4.1.2 Change the parameter:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> - &nbsp;<em>PermitRootLogin prohibit-password</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>to</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp;- PermitRootLogin no</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To block the root access login in ssh</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4.1.3 Uncomment as well the parameter&nbsp;<em>PubkeyAuthentication yes</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>to allow ssh access via pair Private/Public key.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. Firewall setup</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>#See open ports\n&gt;: sudo ss -tupln\n\n#Install ufw\n&gt;: sudo apt ufw\n\n#Get the ufw status\n&gt;: sudo ufw status\n\n#Allow por through firewall\n&gt;: sudo ufw allow &lt;port_number&gt;\n\n#Active firewall\n&gt;: sudo ufw enable\n\n#Reload firewall \n&gt;: sudo ufw reload</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6. Block pings</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>#Edit the ufw configuration file\n&gt;: sudo vim /etc/ufw/before.rules\n\n#Add this line \n-A ufw-before-input -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -j DROP\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Done! Now you have some security level in your juice linux server!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cheers!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Making your Linux home server more \"safe\"','','publish','open','open','','making-your-linux-home-server-more-safe','','','2023-04-08 22:36:40','2023-04-08 22:36:40','',0,'http://deviofuzz.local/?p=143',0,'post','',0);
